00:55:56.020 --> 00:55:56.470
HAL VARIAN: All right.

00:55:56.470 --> 00:55:57.580
Last question.

00:55:57.580 --> 00:56:00.170
How can we improve the teaching
of statistics?

00:56:00.170 --> 00:56:01.280
NATE SILVER: That's
a big question,

00:56:01.280 --> 00:56:02.250
an important question.

00:56:02.250 --> 00:56:03.800
HAL VARIAN: Important.

00:56:03.800 --> 00:56:07.430
NATE SILVER: And I'm not sure
why statistics education or

00:56:07.430 --> 00:56:12.660
math eduction in general is so
abstract in this country.

00:56:12.660 --> 00:56:16.830
I think you should just kind of
give kids data and let them

00:56:16.830 --> 00:56:18.780
play around with it,
at a certain level.

00:56:18.780 --> 00:56:20.590
And I don't know exactly what
type of data you'd give to a

00:56:20.590 --> 00:56:24.990
high-school class exactly, but
to have kids conduct a survey

00:56:24.990 --> 00:56:28.040
or to have kids just start
counting things to come to

00:56:28.040 --> 00:56:28.820
some conclusions about them.

00:56:28.820 --> 00:56:33.160
I mean, the fact that people
are phobic of math is odd.

00:56:33.160 --> 00:56:35.180
I get the comment sometimes from
readers on my blog, like,

00:56:35.180 --> 00:56:39.330
oh, I thought I hated math, or
I'm terrible at math, but I

00:56:39.330 --> 00:56:40.080
like your blog.

00:56:40.080 --> 00:56:40.950
You'll hear that.

00:56:40.950 --> 00:56:43.970
And probably, that person
is not terrible at math.

00:56:43.970 --> 00:56:47.860
Probably they had some teacher
who made them dislike math for

00:56:47.860 --> 00:56:51.000
some reason along the way,
because it wasn't taught in a

00:56:51.000 --> 00:56:53.810
way that it had practical,
real-world applications.

00:56:53.810 --> 00:56:56.620
And I hope that will change.

00:56:56.620 --> 00:56:58.810
I don't know enough about what
different curriculum

